Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2 — Intercept back navigation and conditionally cancel it:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/software back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Intercepts Shell navigation (back gesture, URI navigation, etc.)
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();   // pause navigation

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();                   // cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();              // resume Shell pipeline
    }

    // Intercepts Android hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // true = we handled it, suppress default behavior
    }
}
```

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, replace the default Shell back button with a toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBack}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBack"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
    <!-- ... -->
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        IsVisible="True"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

With the command in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- **`ShellNavigatingEventArgs.GetDeferral()`** lets you go async before deciding to cancel.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** is Android-only (hardware/gesture back); the `Shell.Navigating` handler covers all platforms.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride`** replaces the arrow with your label. Setting `Command` bypasses the default pop, giving you full control.
